<setup>
  <function name="EQ1" variable="y">0.1*(y-1)*(y-5)</function>
  <function name="EQ2" variable="y">-0.1*(y-2)*(y-6)</function>
  <mathList name="eqSols1">1 5</mathList>
  <mathList name="eqSols2">2 6</mathList>
  <selectFromSequence name="a" from="1" to="6" exclude="3 4"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="b" from="1" to="6" exclude="3 4 $a"/>  
  <selectFromSequence name="c" from="1" to="6" exclude="3 4 $a $b"/>  
  <selectFromSequence name="d" from="1" to="6" exclude="3 4 $a $b $c"/>  
  <selectFromSequence name="k" from="1" to="2"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="y0" from="3" to="4"/>
</setup>
<p>
  Consider the two slope fields for the respective differential equations (1), at left, and (2), at right, that are given in the images above.
</p>

<p>
  <ol marker="a.">
    <li>
      <p>
        For differential equation (1), identify all equilibrium solutions.  If there's more than one, separate your answers with commas; if there are none, enter <q>none</q>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Equilibrium solutions: <m>y = </m><mathInput name="enteredEq1"/><answer unorderedCompare><award><when>$enteredEq1=$eqSols1</when></award></answer>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        For differential equation (2), identify all equilibrium solutions.  If there's more than one, separate your answers with commas; if there are none, enter <q>none</q>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Equilibrium solutions: <m>y = </m><mathInput name="enteredEq2"/><answer unorderedCompare><award><when>$enteredEq2=$eqSols2</when></award></answer>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Classify the stability of each of the equilibrium solutions from the two given differential equations' slope fields.
      </p>
      <p>
        The equilibrium solution <m>y = $a</m> is <choiceInput inline name="ans1">
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>stable</choice>
          <choice>unstable</choice>
          <choice>semi-stable</choice>
        </choiceInput>
      </p>
      <p>
        The equilibrium solution <m>y = $b</m> is <choiceInput inline name="ans2">
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>stable</choice>
          <choice>unstable</choice>
          <choice>semi-stable</choice>
        </choiceInput>
      </p>
      <p>
        The equilibrium solution <m>y = $c</m> is <choiceInput inline name="ans3">
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>stable</choice>
          <choice>unstable</choice>
          <choice>semi-stable</choice>
        </choiceInput>
      </p>
      <p>
        The equilibrium solution <m>y = $d</m> is <choiceInput inline name="ans4">
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>stable</choice>
          <choice>unstable</choice>
          <choice>semi-stable</choice>
        </choiceInput>
      </p>
      <p>
        <answer><award><when>
          (($a=1 or $a=6) and ($ans1.selectedIndices=2) or 
           ($a=2 or $a=5) and ($ans1.selectedIndices=3))
          and
          (($b=1 or $b=6) and ($ans2.selectedIndices=2) or 
           ($b=2 or $b=5) and ($ans2.selectedIndices=3))
          and
          (($c=1 or $c=6) and ($ans3.selectedIndices=2) or 
           ($c=2 or $c=5) and ($ans3.selectedIndices=3))
          and
          (($d=1 or $d=6) and ($ans4.selectedIndices=2) or 
           ($d=2 or $d=5) and ($ans4.selectedIndices=3))
        </when></award></answer>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Consider a function that is a solution to differential equation <m>($k)</m> and that satisfies <m>y(0) = $y0</m>.  Based on the relevant slope field, we expect that the solution function <m>y(t)</m> will be 
        <choiceInput name="incdec">
          <choice>always increasing</choice>
          <choice>always decreasing</choice>
          <choice>sometimes increasing, sometimes decreasing</choice>
          <choice>always constant</choice>
        </choiceInput>
      </p>
      <p>
        <answer><award><when>
          ($k=1 and $incdec.selectedIndices=2) or ($k=2 and $incdec.selectedIndices=1)
        </when></award></answer>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
</p>
